4.0 PHASE 2: INTEGRATED PROTOTYPE

4.1 Design Evolution Based on Phase 1 Results

Three Potential Design Paths:

Path A: Full Hybrid System (Both criteria met)

```
- Incorporate all three separation mechanisms
- Optimize timing sequence based on Phase 1 data
- Design for 30cm × 30cm operational area
- Target efficiency: >20% at <200W
```

Path B: Vibration-Electrostatic Only (Acoustic failed)

```
- Remove ultrasonic transducers
- Enhance vibration parameters
- Optimize electrostatic field geometry
- Target efficiency: >15% at <150W
```

Path C: Science Instrument Focus (Both criteria failed)

```
- Repurpose as regolith characterization tool
- Acoustic tomography capability
- Sample manipulation for analysis
- Scientific value rather than ISRU
```

4.2 Integrated System Design Details

Mechanical Design:

```
Frame: Aluminum 6061-T6, black anodized
  - Dimensions: 40cm × 40cm × 20cm (external)
  - Weight: 15 kg (excluding cryocooler)
  - Mounting: Vibration isolated with Sorbothane feet
  
Layers (stacked assembly):
1. Base plate: 10mm aluminum, mounting for shaker
2. Regolith container: 30cm × 30cm × 5mm depth
3. Transducer array: 8×8 PZT on 3mm alumina substrate
4. Electrode assembly: Quadrupole on G10 insulators
5. Collection hood: Removable for sample access
6. Top cover: With viewports and feedthroughs
```

Thermal Design for Integrated System:

```
Cooling strategy: Two-stage approach
Stage 1: Regolith bed cooling
  - Direct contact with copper cold plate
  - Temperature: 100K ± 0.5K
  - Cooling power: 5W required
  
Stage 2: Component cooling
  - Transducers: Active heating to maintain 150K
  - Electronics: Warm enclosures at 300K
  - Thermal breaks: G10 standoffs throughout
  
Heat loads estimation:
  - Vibration: 10W (mechanical losses)
  - Acoustics: 20W (transducer heating)
  - Electrostatics: 5W (corona discharge)
  - Parasitic: 2W (conduction through supports)
  - Total: 37W → requires 10W cooling at 100K
```

Control System Architecture:

```
Hardware:
- Controller: National Instruments cRIO-9045
  - CPU: Intel Atom quad-core 1.33 GHz
  - FPGA: Spartan-6
  - I/O: 8 slots for modular cards
  
I/O Configuration:
1. Analog input: 32 channels, 24-bit, 50 kS/s
2. Analog output: 8 channels, 16-bit, 100 kS/s
3. Digital I/O: 64 channels, 5V TTL
4. Counter/timer: 8 channels, 80 MHz
5. Communication: Ethernet, RS-232, RS-485

Software architecture:
- Real-time: LabVIEW FPGA for timing-critical tasks
- User interface: Python/React web application
- Data management: PostgreSQL with TimescaleDB extension
- Analysis: Jupyter notebooks for post-processing
```

4.3 Performance Testing Protocol

Test Sequence for Integrated System:

```
Phase 1: Subsystem verification
1. Vibration system: Verify fluidization at 100K
2. Acoustic system: Measure field uniformity
3. Electrostatic system: Verify field distribution
4. Thermal system: Validate temperature stability

Phase 2: Component testing
1. Vibration only: Measure ice liberation efficiency
2. Vibration + acoustics: Test density-based separation
3. Vibration + electrostatic: Test charge-based separation
4. Full hybrid: All mechanisms active

Phase 3: Optimization
1. Timing optimization: Vary sequence durations
2. Parameter sweep: Amplitude, frequency, voltage
3. Environmental testing: Different temperatures (80-120K)
4. Mixture variations: 1%, 3%, 5% ice content

Phase 4: Endurance testing
1. Continuous operation: 24 hours
2. Cycling test: 1000 on/off cycles
3. Performance degradation: Monitor efficiency over time
4. Failure mode testing: Intentional fault injection
```

Performance Metrics:

```
Primary metric: Separation efficiency
  η = (mass of ice collected) / (initial ice mass) × 100%
  
Secondary metrics:
1. Power consumption: W per gram of ice
2. Purity: Ice fraction in collected material
3. Throughput: Grams per hour
4. Thermal load: Watts rejected at 100K
5. Reliability: Mean time between failures
  
Measurement methods:
1. Mass measurement: Microbalance (0.1 mg resolution)
2. Composition analysis: Heated collection with mass spec
3. Power measurement: Precision power analyzer
4. Thermal measurement: Heat flux sensors
```

4.4 Data Analysis Methodology

Statistical Analysis:

```
Sample size: n=10 for each test condition
Confidence intervals: 95% using Student's t-distribution
Outlier detection: Grubbs' test (α=0.05)
Error propagation: Monte Carlo simulation for derived quantities

Key analyses:
1. ANOVA: Effect of different parameters on efficiency
2. Regression: Modeling efficiency as function of power
3. Optimization: Response surface methodology
4. Uncertainty quantification: Bayesian inference
```

Model Validation:

```
Compare experimental results with:
1. COMSOL multiphysics simulations
2. Discrete element method (DEM) models
3. Analytical models based on first principles

Validation metrics:
1. R² value for model-experiment correlation
2. Root mean square error (RMSE)
3. Mean absolute percentage error (MAPE)
```

---

5.0 SAFETY PROTOCOLS

5.1 Electrical Safety

High Voltage (5-10 kV) Protocols:

```
1. Interlocked enclosures: Doors disable HV when open
2. Grounding: All equipment bonded to common ground
3. Discharge sticks: Available at all HV locations
4. Warning signs: Clear labeling of HV areas
5. Training: All personnel certified for HV work
```

Cryogenic Safety:

```
1. Cold handling: Insulated gloves and face shields
2. Oxygen monitoring: Continuous O₂ level measurement
3. Ventilation: Adequate room ventilation for gas release
4. Emergency procedures: Evacuation routes and contact information
```

Vacuum Safety:

```
1. Implosion shielding: Polycarbonate shields around viewports
2. Pressure interlocks: Prevent opening under vacuum
3. Leak checking: Regular helium leak detection
4. Burst disk: Pressure relief for over-pressure events
```

5.2 Operational Safety

Daily Checklist:

```
1. Visual inspection of all components
2. Verification of safety interlocks
3. Check of emergency stop functionality
4. Review of experiment parameters
5. Confirmation of data logging operation
```

Emergency Procedures:

```
Power failure: Automatic safe shutdown sequence
Vacuum failure: Automatic venting to prevent contamination
Over-temperature: Automatic heating shutdown
Over-pressure: Burst disk and relief valves
Personnel injury: Clearly marked emergency contacts and procedures
```

